# COGNET LDI Engine — Architecture Rules

## Architectural Pattern: Modular Monolith

This is a **modular monolith** — one deployable unit with enforced internal domain boundaries. It is not microservices. Do not introduce service meshes, message buses between domains, inter-service HTTP calls, or distributed transaction patterns before the MVP first flow is end-to-end functional.

If a refactor toward service extraction is considered, that decision must be explicitly documented and approved — it is not an incidental implementation choice.

## Directory Structure — Canonical Domain Layout

```
cognet/
├── apps/
│   ├── api/                        # FastAPI application
│   │   └── app/
│   │       ├── models/             # SQLAlchemy ORM models (single source of truth for DB schema)
│   │       ├── routers/            # Route definitions — thin, delegate to services
│   │       ├── dependencies/       # FastAPI dependency injection
│   │       └── main.py
│   └── admin/                      # Next.js admin UI
│       ├── locales/
│       │   ├── en/
│       │   └── he/
│       ├── components/
│       ├── pages/ (or app/)
│       └── lib/api/                # Typed API client — all backend calls go here
├── services/                       # Domain service logic (no FastAPI imports)
│   ├── ingestion/
│   ├── normalization/
│   ├── enrichment/
│   ├── taxonomy/
│   ├── signals/
│   ├── agents/
│   ├── ranking/
│   ├── opportunities/
│   ├── orchestration/
│   ├── observability/
│   ├── localization/
│   ├── governance/
│   └── evaluation/
└── shared/
    ├── contracts/                  # Request/response schemas (Pydantic)
    ├── schemas/                    # Internal data transfer schemas
    ├── enums/                      # Shared enumerations
    └── models/                     # Shared base model utilities
```

## Import Rules — Enforced Boundaries

| From | May import | Must NOT import |
|---|---|---|
| `apps/api/` | `services/**`, `shared/**` | nothing from `apps/admin/` |
| `apps/admin/` | `apps/admin/lib/api/` (typed client only) | `services/**` directly, `apps/api/` directly |
| `services/**` | `shared/**`, other `services/**` with explicit justification | `apps/api/`, `apps/admin/` |
| `shared/**` | stdlib, third-party only | `apps/**`, `services/**` |

**Cross-domain service imports** (e.g., `signals` importing from `ingestion`) must be documented with a comment explaining the dependency. If two domains are heavily coupled, they may need to be merged into one.

## API Layer Rules

- Routers in `apps/api/app/routers/` must be **thin** — route handlers call service functions, they do not contain business logic
- All request and response schemas must be defined as Pydantic models in `shared/contracts/`
- API versioning: prefix all routes with `/v1/` from the start — do not add versioning retroactively
- Every route must have: response model declared, status codes declared, docstring with purpose
- Authentication and authorization must be handled via FastAPI dependencies — not inline in route handlers

## Database and ORM Rules

- SQLAlchemy models live exclusively in `apps/api/app/models/` — this is the single source of truth for the DB schema
- Services access the database via a **repository pattern** — no raw SQLAlchemy session calls scattered in service logic
- Every repository class must be in `services/{domain}/repository.py` and accept a `session` dependency
- Alembic migration files must be generated from model changes — no hand-written migrations that diverge from models
- Every migration must have a descriptive message: `alembic revision --autogenerate -m "add_opportunity_classification_index"`

## Admin UI Rules

- All backend calls from `apps/admin/` must go through `apps/admin/lib/api/` — no scattered `fetch()` or `axios` calls in components or pages
- The typed API client must match the `shared/contracts/` schemas — if the contract changes, the client must be updated in the same PR
- No hardcoded backend URLs in components — use environment variables (`NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL`)

## Completeness Requirement

A feature is only considered complete when ALL of the following exist:

1. Domain service logic in `services/{domain}/`
2. Pydantic contract in `shared/contracts/` (if externally consumed)
3. Repository method in `services/{domain}/repository.py` (if DB access needed)
4. API route in `apps/api/app/routers/` (if surfaced externally)
5. Structured logging at entry, exit, and failure points
6. Explicit failure handling — no bare `except: pass` or silent swallowing of errors
7. Alembic migration (if new DB schema)
8. At minimum, a smoke test covering the happy path

A disconnected class with no integration = incomplete. A documented feature with no code = incomplete.
